<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<!DOCTYPE plist PUBLIC "-//Apple//DTD PLIST 1.0//EN" "http://www.apple.com/DTDs/PropertyList-1.0.dtd">
<!--
  Mac App Store entitlements for the main FileFlow process.

  These are the *minimum* set required for an offline file-organizer:
  no networking, no microphone/camera, no AppleEvents, no JIT (V8 still
  works under the hardened runtime via allow-jit + allow-unsigned-exec
  below). Apple's reviewer will reject anything broader without
  documented justification, so we keep the surface small.

  WHY EACH KEY:

    com.apple.security.app-sandbox
        The single key that switches the macOS app sandbox on. Required
        for every MAS submission. Without this the bundle is rejected
        before review.

    com.apple.security.files.user-selected.read-write
        Lets us read and write any folder the user explicitly grants via
        Powerbox (i.e. the system file/directory picker). This is the
        ONLY way a sandboxed app gets at user files outside its container.
        FileFlow's Settings flow opens dialog.showOpenDialog —
        whichever directory the user picks lands here.

    com.apple.security.files.bookmarks.app-scope
        Lets the app *persist* the user's grant across launches. Without
        this, the user would have to re-pick every watched folder every
        time they open the app. The flow is:
          1. dialog.showOpenDialog returns a security-scoped bookmark
          2. We base64-encode and stash it in config
          3. On next launch we call app.startAccessingSecurityScopedResource
             with that bookmark to re-acquire access
        See electron/bookmarks.ts for the runtime side.

    com.apple.security.cs.allow-jit
    com.apple.security.cs.allow-unsigned-executable-memory
        Required by V8. Electron won't start under the hardened runtime
        without these. They sound scary but they're standard for every
        Electron MAS app — the hardened runtime is still enforced for
        everything else (library validation, dyld injection, etc.).

  WHAT'S DELIBERATELY OMITTED:

    com.apple.security.network.client
        FileFlow makes zero outbound HTTP/HTTPS calls. No telemetry, no
        update checks, no remote config. Adding this would force us to
        explain it during review. We don't need it.

    com.apple.security.files.downloads.read-write
    com.apple.security.assets.{music,movies,pictures}.*
        Special-folder shortcuts that pre-grant access to specific user
        folders without a Powerbox prompt. Tempting but a reviewer will
        ask "why does a file organizer need automatic Downloads access?"
        and we'd have to argue. The user-selected entitlement above
        covers the same ground via an explicit prompt — better optics,
        smaller threat surface.
-->
<plist version="1.0">
<dict>
  <key>com.apple.security.app-sandbox</key>
  <true/>

  <key>com.apple.security.files.user-selected.read-write</key>
  <true/>

  <key>com.apple.security.files.bookmarks.app-scope</key>
  <true/>

  <key>com.apple.security.cs.allow-jit</key>
  <true/>

  <key>com.apple.security.cs.allow-unsigned-executable-memory</key>
  <true/>
</dict>
</plist>
